      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Arguments suggesting a strong genetic component often rely on twin and adoption studies to estimate heritability of cognitive traits. Proponents point to heritability estimates for IQ that can be quite high within populations, implying a significant biological influence on individual differences. These researchers typically argue that even after controlling for environmental factors, a measurable genetic variance remains, which they then link to group mean differences. However, critics argue that these models often fail to account for complex gene-environment interactions and confounding social variables.",
      "source": "target",
