      "content": "Advocates like Jensen and Murray often argue that when controlling for basic environmental factors, statistical analyses of IQ scores demonstrate persistent, measurable disparities between racial groups. Their conclusion tends to be that these persistent gaps suggest a biologically rooted hierarchy in average cognitive functioning across different populations. These perspectives emphasize the statistical patterns found in large-scale testing data to support the concept of inherent differences in average intelligence. Nevertheless, these conclusions remain subjects of intense scientific contention due to the controversies surrounding their methodologies and interpretations.",
